Social accounting matrix (SAM) contains data for firms, households and government which are organized in a way to represent the interactions of all three entities in a typical economy.

BB is a matrix which describes how investment in physical infrastructure is transformed into functioning capital such as commercial and residential buildings. These data are collected from the Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA).
IOUT is a matrix that describes the transfer of tax revenue collected by the local government to help finance local government expenditures.
MISC is the name of a file that contains data for commercial sector employment and physical capital. It also contains data for the number of households and working households in the economy.
MISCH is a file that contains elasticities for the supply of labor with respect to paying income taxes.
EMPLOY is a table name containing data for commercial sector employment.
JOBCR is a matrix describing the supply of workers coming from each household group in the economy.
OUTCR is a matrix describing the number of workers who live in Galveston but commute outside of town to work.
